df['year_updated']=df['timestamp_updated'].apply(lambda x:str(x).split('-')[0])

# As I am not certain about the values of CURRENT GRADE, I will one-hot encode these columns

oh_encode = ['CITY','INSPECTION_TYPE','RESTAURANT_CATEGORY', 'CURRENT_GRADE']
# for OH_encode columns, I will be imputing the null values with 'N/A' for now
data[oh_encode]=data[oh_encode].fillna('N/A')

# for 'Number of violations', the proportion of low inspection grade was similar to that of value 8-9 and 15-16.
# looking at the distribution of the data, the data is right-skewed. Thus, I will impute the missing value with 8-9, which we see more often
data['NUMBER_OF_VIOLATIONS'] = data['NUMBER_OF_VIOLATIONS'].fillna(8)
#data['NUMBER_OF_VIOLATIONS'] = data['NUMBER_OF_VIOLATIONS'].fillna(data['NUMBER_OF_VIOLATIONS'].median())


# for 'CURRENT_DEMERITS' and 'INSPECTION_DEMERITS', the proportion of low inspection grade is same as 11 and 14 respectively
data['CURRENT_DEMERITS'] = data['CURRENT_DEMERITS'].fillna(11)
data['INSPECTION_DEMERITS'] = data['INSPECTION_DEMERITS'].fillna(14)
#data['CURRENT_DEMERITS'] = data['CURRENT_DEMERITS'].fillna(data['CURRENT_DEMERITS'].median())
#data['INSPECTION_DEMERITS'] = data['INSPECTION_DEMERITS'].fillna(data['INSPECTION_DEMERITS'].median())


violation_scale = {"Imminent Health Hazard":20, "Critical":6,"Major":3,"Non-Major":1}
data[['FIRST_VIOLATION_TYPE','SECOND_VIOLATION_TYPE','THIRD_VIOLATION_TYPE']] = data[['FIRST_VIOLATION_TYPE','SECOND_VIOLATION_TYPE','THIRD_VIOLATION_TYPE']].replace(violation_scale, regex=True)
# for the 3 columns above, we saw that number of low inspection grade for null values were not very different from either 'Major' or 'Non Major'
# thus I will impute the null values with the median for each columns
data.FIRST_VIOLATION_TYPE=data.FIRST_VIOLATION_TYPE.fillna(data.FIRST_VIOLATION_TYPE.median())
data.SECOND_VIOLATION_TYPE=data.SECOND_VIOLATION_TYPE.fillna(data.SECOND_VIOLATION_TYPE.median())
data.THIRD_VIOLATION_TYPE=data.THIRD_VIOLATION_TYPE.fillna(data.THIRD_VIOLATION_TYPE.median())

# new column introduced to count the violations  
data['Violation_Raw_Count'] = all_data.VIOLATIONS_RAW.apply(lambda x:len(str(x).split(',')))


data['EMPLOYEE_COUNT'] = all_data['EMPLOYEE_COUNT'].fillna(all_data['EMPLOYEE_COUNT'].median())
data['MEDIAN_EMPLOYEE_AGE'] = all_data['MEDIAN_EMPLOYEE_AGE'].fillna(all_data['MEDIAN_EMPLOYEE_AGE'].median())
data['MEDIAN_EMPLOYEE_TENURE'] = all_data['MEDIAN_EMPLOYEE_TENURE'].fillna(all_data['MEDIAN_EMPLOYEE_TENURE'].median())

Model Building / Accuracy¶

Although widely used, classification accuracy is almost universally inappropriate for imbalanced classification. The reason is, a high accuracy (or low error) is achievable by a no skill model that only predicts the majority class.

Alternatively, we can look at Precision-Recall Metrics (Precision, Recall, F1 score)

In [913]:
y =  new_df.y
new_df = new_df.drop(columns = 'y')

train_x, test_x, train_y, test_y = train_test_split(new_df, y)
In [914]:
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score

from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix
from sklearn.metrics import classification_report

#class_weight hyperparameter is used to deal with unbalanced data
classifier = RandomForestClassifier(class_weight='balanced')
classifier.fit(train_x, train_y)
print(classifier.score(train_x,train_y))
pred = classifier.predict(test_x)
print("Accuracy: ",accuracy_score(test_y, pred))

cm = confusion_matrix(test_y, pred)
plt.rcParams['figure.figsize'] = (5, 5)

from sklearn.model_selection import KFold, cross_val_score, train_test_split, RepeatedKFold, StratifiedKFold

def accuracy_cv(model):
    kf = RepeatedKFold(n_splits=5, n_repeats=3, random_state=1)
    scv = StratifiedKFold(n_splits=5)
    accuracy= cross_val_score(model, new_df, y, scoring="accuracy", cv = scv)
    return(accuracy)

metric_names = ['f1', 'roc_auc', 'average_precision', 'accuracy', 'precision', 'recall']
scores_df = pd.DataFrame(index=metric_names, columns=['Stratified-CV']) # to store the scores
scv = StratifiedKFold(n_splits=5)

from sklearn.metrics import roc_curve
from sklearn.metrics import auc

classifier = RandomForestClassifier(class_weight='balanced')
classifier.fit(train_x, train_y)
pred = classifier.predict(test_x)

y_pred_quant = classifier.predict_proba(test_x)[:, 1]
fpr, tpr, thresholds = roc_curve(test_y, y_pred_quant)

fig, ax = plt.subplots()
ax.plot(fpr, tpr)
ax.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], transform=ax.transAxes, ls="-", c=".3")
plt.xlim([0.0, 1.0])
plt.ylim([0.0, 1.0])

plt.rcParams['figure.figsize'] = (8, 8)
plt.title('ROC curve for RandomForest classifier', fontweight = 30)
plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate (1 - Specificity)')
plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate (Sensitivity)')
plt.show()


auc = auc(fpr, tpr)
print("AUC Score :", auc)

Recommendation for improving the data¶

  1. Meta Data is needed to explain the values within each of the columns listed
  2. Missing values in the data needs to be addressed
  3. Zipcode needs to have a uniform format
  4. There are values in the VIOLATION_RAW column which does not exists in the external dataset (https://opendataportal-lasvegas.opendata.arcgis.com/datasets/restaurant-inspection-violation-codes)
  5. The value for VIOLATION_RAW needs to be integers separated by comma
  6. The values for certain columns are wrong. (ex. First Violation Type == 1)
  7. We need few more column to understand the seriousness/ demerits of different violation types. Information can be found from the source below (https://opendataportal-lasvegas.opendata.arcgis.com/datasets/restaurant-inspection-violation-codes)
  8. Columns could be formatted in more accurate data types
  9. We could always use more data to provide more accurate classification
